Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Lower Taxes Lure More U.S. Firms Abroad

PARAGRAPH.#text: Politicians have been paying plenty of lip service to cutting corporate taxes in the U.S., but some companies are voting with their feet. Since 2009, at least 10 U.S. public companies have moved their incorporation address abroad or announced plans to do so -- up from just a handful from 2004 through 2008, the Journal's John D. Mackinnon and Scott Thurm report. Ensco International cut its effective tax rate to 10.5% in Q2, down from 19% in 2009, after moving from Dallas to the U.K. The savings: more than $100 million a year. The oil company was following in the footsteps of rivals Transocean, Noble and Weatherford International who were already taking advantage of more favorable tax rates overseas.
